vectorData.altText: That's right!  The parotid duct (D) runs horizontally across the superficial surface of the masseter.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
You will find the parotid duct about a finger’s breadth inferior to the zygomatic arch, and running roughly parallel to it. It is a little thinner than a pencil.
Your first task will be to identify the parotid duct (A) and branches of the facial nerve (B) superficial to the masseter muscle (C).

Clean it by blunt dissection, moving your instruments parallel to the duct and adjacent branches of the facial nerve. This way, you are less likely to sever them. 
You may encounter and clean a few branches of the facial nerve as you work, but do not try to complete a full dissection of the branches of the facial nerve. 
An exceptional dissection demonstrating all motor branches of the facial nerve is available in Grant’s Museum and is part of your Field Trip.
